Linux System Information & Monitoring Commands

df -T or lsblk -f or blkid ‚Üí Show file system types which are mounted

1 Byte = 8 bits
1 KB = 1024 Bytes
1 MB = 1024 KB
1 GB = 1024 MB
1 TB = 1024 GB
1 PB = 1024 TB PB means PetaByte
1 EB = 1024 PB EB means ExaByte
1 ZB = 1024 EB ZB means ZettaByte
1 YB = 1024 ZB YB means YottaByte

Mnemonic to remember the order of units:
Big Kangaroos Make Great Tiny Puppies Eat Zebras Yearly.

| Shortcut  | Action                                       |
| --------- | -------------------------------------------- |
| Ctrl + A  | Move cursor to beginning of line             |
| Ctrl + E  | Move cursor to end of line                   |
| Alt + B   | Move cursor back one word                    |
| Alt + F   | Move cursor forward one word                 |
| Ctrl + K  | Delete from cursor to end of line            |
| Ctrl + U  | Delete from cursor to beginning of line      |
| Ctrl + W  | Delete word before cursor                    |
| Alt + D   | Delete word after cursor                     |
| Ctrl + Y  | Paste last deleted text                      |
| Ctrl + L  | Clear screen (same as `clear`)               |
| Ctrl + T  | Swap characters before and under cursor      |
| Ctrl + _  | Undo last editing action                     |
| Esc + .   | Insert last argument of previous command     |
| Ctrl + D  | Exit the shell (logout)                      |
| Ctrl + C  | Cancel current command                       |
| Ctrl + Z  | Suspend current command(put it in background)|

$$ ‚Üí Current shell process ID
Used to get the process ID of the current shell script or command.

!! ‚Üí Last command executed
!$ ‚Üí Last argument of the last command
!^ ‚Üí First argument of the last command

!x ‚Üí Last command starting with 'x'
!ansible:p ‚Üí Last command starting with 'ansible' and print it

$ git comit -m "oops"
$ ^comit^commit   # -> git commit -m "oops"

!-3:2 ‚Üí Third command from the end, second argument

!?docker? ‚Üí Last command containing 'docker'

set -o histexpand # To expand command press Ctrl+Alt+e 
bind 'Space:magic-space' # To expand command press Space in ~/.bashrc

export PS1="\u@\h:\w\$ " --> primary prompt string in the shell 
echo 'export PS1="\u@\h:\w$ "' >> ~/.bashrc
source ~/.bashrc

echo '"\C-t": "\C-e\C-u"' >> .inputrc
bind -f ~/.inputrc

vim :
The quick brown fox --> The cursor is at q
dw ‚Üí deletes "quick"
de ‚Üí deletes "quick" (differs when punctuation involved)
daw ‚Üí deletes " quick"
diw ‚Üí deletes just "quick"
d$	Delete to end of line
d0	Delete to absolute beginning of line
dG  ‚Üí Delete to end of file

34gg --> Go to 34th line number

gg=G ‚Üí Indent the entire file
5== ‚Üí Indent the current line and the next 4 lines
V3j= ‚Üí Indent the current line and the next 3 lines

sudo !! is just a special case using word-designator !! (whole previous line). Saves re-typing a failed ‚Äúpermission denied‚Äù command.

uname - Display System Information
    uname -s ‚Üí Show kernel name
	uname -a ‚Üí Shows all system information
	uname -r ‚Üí Displays the kernel release version
	uname -m ‚Üí Displays the machine hardware name/architecture
	uname -n ‚Üí Shows the hostname
	uname -o ‚Üí Displays the operating system name
	uname -v ‚Üí Shows the kernel version
	uname -p ‚Üí Displays the processor type
	uname -i ‚Üí Displays the hardware platform 

uptime - Check System Uptime
	uptime -p ‚Üí Pretty format -> Shows uptime in a human-readable format (e.g., "up 3 hours, 15 minutes")
	uptime -s ‚Üí Since format -> Displays the system start time (e.g., "2024-04-01 08:30:00")
	uptime -V ‚Üí Version -> Shows the version of the uptime command

Display CPU Information
	nproc ‚Üí Show the number of processing units available
	nproc --all ‚Üí Show all processing units, including offline ones

hostname - Display and Set Hostname
hostnamectl ‚Üí Show system hostname and related information

Modify Hostname:
sudo hostnamectl set-hostname --static new-hostname  
--static -> Set the static hostname for permanent use
--transient -> Set the transient hostname for temporary use
--pretty -> Set the pretty hostname for display purposes
Make it permanent by editing /etc/hostname and /etc/hosts.

Useful Options:
	hostname -s ‚Üí Short hostname (without domain)
	hostname -f ‚Üí Fully qualified domain name (FQDN)
	hostname -I ‚Üí IP address(es)
	hostname -d ‚Üí DNS Domain name
	hostname -A ‚Üí All known hostnames

System Reboot History
    last reboot ‚Üí History of system reboots 
    last -x | grep reboot ‚Üí Show all reboots 
	-x means "show extended information"
    last -x | grep shutdown ‚Üí Show all shutdowns
    last -x | grep runlevel ‚Üí Show all runlevel changes 
	Runlevel means the state of the system
	0 ‚Üí Halt, 1 ‚Üí Single-user mode, 2 ‚Üí Multi-user mode, 3 ‚Üí Full multi-user mode, 4 ‚Üí Unused, 5 ‚Üí Graphical mode, 6 ‚Üí Reboot
	last -x | grep runlevel | awk '{print $5,$6,$7,$8}' | date -f - +"%Y-%m-%d %I:%M:%S %p" 
    last -x | grep shutdown | awk '{print $5,$6,$7,$8}' | date -f - +"%Y-%m-%d %I:%M:%S %p" 
    ‚Üí Show shutdown times in a readable format

Check Primary System IP Address:
hostname -I | awk '{print $1}'

Network Commands
	ip addr ‚Üí Show IP addresses and network interfaces
	ifconfig ‚Üí (Deprecated) Display network configuration
    ip addr show dev eth0 ‚Üí Show IP address for a specific interface`
    ip neigh show ‚Üí Show ARP cache which show MAC address on the network
	ARP means Address Resolution Protocol it is used to find the MAC address of a host
	ip link show ‚Üí Show all network interfaces & MAC on the local system
    ip link set eth0 up ‚Üí Bring up a specific interface
    ip link set eth0 down ‚Üí Bring down a specific interface

date - Display and Format Date/Time
Common Formatting Flags:
Flag	Description				   Example
%d		Day of month (01-31)		03
%m		Month (01-12)				04
%y		Year (2-digit)				25
%Y		Year (4-digit)				2025
%A		Full weekday name			Thursday
%a		Abbreviated weekday name	Thu
%B		Full month name				April
%b		Abbreviated month name		Apr
%H		Hour (00-23)				14
%I		Hour (01-12)				02
%M		Minutes (00-59)				30
%S		Seconds (00-59)				45
%p		AM/PM						PM
%Z		Time zone					UTC means Coordinated Universal Time
%F      ISO Date (%Y-%m-%d)	        2025-06-28
%T		Time (%H:%M:%S)				14:45:05

Show Time with Milliseconds:
date +"%H:%M:%S:%3N" 
date +"%I:%M:%S:%3N"
date -f - means "read date strings from the input piped to me"
-f means "file input"
date -f input.txt -> Read from text file
date -d "2024-04-03 10:15:00" +"%Y-%m-%d %I:%M:%S %p"
-d means "display the date in a specific format"
Eg : last reboot | awk '{print $5,$6,$7,$8}' | date -f - +"%Y-%m-%d %I:%M:%S %p"

date +%s -> Show current epoch time
It is commonly used in computing and programming to represent time in a standardized format.

date -d "2024-04-03 10:15:00" +%s
Convert Epoch Time to Normal time:
date -d @1745209628 --> Mon Apr 21 09:57:08 AM IST 2025
@ means "epoch time" in the date command

sudo timedatectl set-timezone Asia/Kolkata -> Set timezone
timedatectl list-timezones ‚Üí List all time zones
timedatectl set-ntp true ‚Üí Enable NTP synchronization
timedatectl set-ntp false ‚Üí Disable NTP synchronization
timedatectl show-timesync ‚Üí Show NTP synchronization status
timedatectl set-time "2024-04-03 10:15:00" ‚Üí Set system time

